The Pandemic Pivot
------------------

Wallner grew up in Hoboken and attended private school in downtown Manhatta=
n, then Colgate
University, followed by a career in the salt mines of content creation. Her=
 journey to Dimepiece began in 2019, when she was working in marketing at S=
otheby=E2=80=99s, creating editorial content for the watches team, and perc=
eived a lack of watch marketing directed toward women. =E2=80=9CWomen weren=
=E2=80=99t central to the narrative at all,=E2=80=9D she told me. She becam=
e interested in timepieces and began learning about them=E2=80=94the differ=
ent brands, product families, movements, reference numbers, that sort of th=
ing. When
Sotheby=E2=80=99s laid her off at the start of the pandemic, she was able t=
o focus on her new interest without distraction.

The timing was fortuitous. As we know, online watch sales exploded during t=
he pandemic, along with other collectibles markets. It was also a time when=
 companies were being held accountable for not being inclusive. =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m by no means the first female watch journalist,=E2=80=9D she told=
 me, and referenced Roberta Naas, who got her start in the 1980s. =E2=80=9C=
But in 2020, I
could post in a frankly girly way without anybody coming after me.=E2=80=9D

Wallner launched her Instagram in fall 2020, and her website soon after. A =
big moment for women in the watch industry came in February 2021, when Hodi=
nkee=E2=80=99s Cara Barrett published an article calling for watches to be =
unisex=E2=80=94this was a time when cool women favored wearing masculine st=
yles loosely on their wrists, rather than smaller women=E2=80=99s watches. =
The year before, both Patek Philippe and Hublot had
launched styles that were intended to be gender-neutral; Barrett=E2=80=99s =
article brought awareness to the concept, and made it a talking point in th=
e industry. But it=E2=80=99s not as simple as rebranding: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99ve had marketing people hand me a watch and say, It could be a woman=E2=
=80=99s watch, when it totally could not be,=E2=80=9D said Wallner.

Harper=E2=80=99s Bazaar invited Wallner to write a recurring column on coll=
ecting timepieces=E2=80=94a men=E2=80=99s magazine staple in a historic fem=
ale glossy. Her first piece, in
June 2021, was titled, =E2=80=9CIn Defense of Small Watches.=E2=80=9D Brand=
s soon started reaching out to her. The first was Audemars Piguet, which is=
 a =E2=80=9Cvery progressive brand by nature,=E2=80=9D Wallner told me. The=
y have prioritized putting women in executive roles, starting with Ginny Wr=
ight as C.E.O. of the Americas in 2021, then Ilaria Resta as C.E.O. a coupl=
e years later.

Time and Again
--------------

Most of the luxury watch brands you=E2=80=99ve heard of=E2=80=94Patek Phili=
ppe, Cartier, IWC, Jaeger-LeCoultre,
Audemars Piguet, etcetera=E2=80=94were founded in the 19th century, when th=
e industry almost exclusively made pocket watches for men. Women didn=E2=80=
=99t even have pockets back then. At the time, the mechanical movements tha=
t kept accurate time were too large to fit into anything smaller than a poc=
ket watch. Rolex invented the wristwatch as we know it in 1910; it became s=
tandard issue for enlisted men during World War I. Women didn=E2=80=99t rea=
lly start wearing wristwatches until the 1930s, after Jaeger-LeCoultre
created the Calibre 101, the world=E2=80=99s smallest mechanical movement a=
t just 14mm long by 4.8mm wide by 3.4mm thick.

Watches for women are still dictated by size. A =E2=80=9Clady=E2=80=99s wat=
ch=E2=80=9D is defined as any watch smaller than 34 millimeters=E2=80=94usu=
ally built around a battery-powered quartz movement instead of the mechanic=
al complications that make men=E2=80=99s watches rare and collectible, and =
featuring stereotypically =E2=80=9Cfeminine=E2=80=9D design details like mo=
ther-of-pearl. These collections of =E2=80=9Cladies=E2=80=99 watches=E2=80=
=9D are
omnipresent but outdated, not only in design but also messaging. It=E2=80=
=99s no wonder that when Wallner started researching watches in 2019, she f=
ound =E2=80=9Cnothing for someone like me, young and into fashion.=E2=80=9D=
 Now, with her influence, Wallner is pushing for more intentionality in the=
 design rooms. Bulgari is committed to making mechanical watches for women,=
 and has released additional styles containing its proprietary Piccolissimo=
 movement. Tiffany is releasing more=E2=80=94and more fantastical=E2=80=94c=
reations, like
its =E2=80=9CBird on a Flying Tourbillon=E2=80=9D watch, which is in line w=
ith parent company LVMH=E2=80=99s growing focus on horology.

Female consumers are taking notice. They=E2=80=99re not yet collectors in t=
he same way some male watch enthusiasts are=E2=80=94they=E2=80=99re more on=
e or two and done, said Wallner=E2=80=94but with prices skyrocketing for ot=
her luxury items like handbags, they=E2=80=99re looking to watches, which h=
ave more longevity. Wallner pointed out that vintage ladies=E2=80=99 watche=
s are also getting more popular. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sure in April at
the Watches and Wonders trade show in Geneva, there will be some femme-forw=
ard releases=E2=80=94smaller sizes, more gems maybe,=E2=80=9D she said, =E2=
=80=9CThe watch world is really trying.=E2=80=9D

