0;">Banerjee is an Indian American painter and sculptor who transforms coll=
ected objects into otherworldly sculptures. When presented with the Asia So=
ciety=E2=80=99s collection, she was drawn to ancient Chinese, Indian, and J=
apanese figures in stone and bronze, especially decayed ones with missing e=
xtremities. =E2=80=9CIt made the presentation of the collection look like a=
 hospital,=E2=80=9D she told me. Inspired by a 6th-7th century Japanese ter=
racotta warrior wearing a skirt, she created two sculptures with a similar
silhouette from collected objects like gourds, a 19th century gramophone, a=
nd a wood milliner=E2=80=99s head.<br/><br/>Kim, a Korean American painter,=
 was inspired by an 11th-12th century Korean stoneware bottle to extend his=
 ongoing series of celadon paintings. Pindell, a pioneering African America=
n abstractionist, took transformative trips to India and Japan in the 1970s=
 and 1980s, which led to her <em>Autobiography</em> series of collaged post=
cards. Pieces from that body of work are on view alongside
17th century Indian manuscripts and Japanese screens.<br/><br/>I=E2=80=99m =
embarrassed to admit that this marked my first trip to the Asia Society in =
the 20-plus years I=E2=80=99ve lived in Manhattan, so it seems the show=E2=
=80=99s goal of attracting a new audience to the category is already succes=
sful. If you, too, are an Asian art novice, this show is a great place to s=
tart. <em>(Re)Generations</em> is on view through August.=C2=A0</li></ul></=
