><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">Wal=
lner grew up in Hoboken and attended private school in downtown Manhattan, =
then Colgate
University, followed by a career in the salt mines of content creation. Her=
 journey to Dimepiece began in 2019, when she was working in marketing at S=
otheby=E2=80=99s, creating editorial content for the watches team, and perc=
eived a lack of watch marketing directed toward women. =E2=80=9CWomen weren=
=E2=80=99t central to the narrative at all,=E2=80=9D she told me. She becam=
e interested in timepieces and began learning about them=E2=80=94the differ=
ent brands, product families, movements, reference numbers, that sort of th=
ing. When
Sotheby=E2=80=99s laid her off at the start of the pandemic, she was able t=
o focus on her new interest without distraction.<br/><br/>The timing was fo=
rtuitous. As we know, online watch sales exploded during the pandemic, alon=
g with other collectibles markets. It was also a time when companies were b=
eing held accountable for not being inclusive. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m by no m=
eans the first female watch journalist,=E2=80=9D she told me, and reference=
d <strong>Roberta Naas</strong>, who got her start in the 1980s. =E2=80=9CB=
ut in 2020, I
could post in a frankly girly way without anybody coming after me.=E2=80=9D=
<br/><br/>Wallner launched her Instagram in fall 2020, and her website soon=
 after. A big moment for women in the watch industry came in February 2021,=
 when Hodinkee=E2=80=99s <strong>Cara Barrett </strong>published an article=
 calling for watches to be unisex=E2=80=94this was a time when cool women f=
avored wearing masculine styles loosely on their wrists, rather than smalle=
r women=E2=80=99s watches. The year before, both Patek Philippe and Hublot =
had
launched styles that were intended to be gender-neutral; Barrett=E2=80=99s =
article brought awareness to the concept, and made it a talking point in th=
e industry. But it=E2=80=99s not as simple as rebranding: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99ve had marketing people hand me a watch and say, <em>It could be a woman=
=E2=80=99s watch</em>, when it totally could not be,=E2=80=9D said Wallner.=
<br/><br/><em>Harper=E2=80=99s Bazaar</em> invited Wallner to write a recur=
ring column on collecting timepieces=E2=80=94a men=E2=80=99s magazine stapl=
e in a historic female glossy. Her first piece, in
June 2021, was titled, =E2=80=9CIn Defense of Small Watches.=E2=80=9D Brand=
s soon started reaching out to her. The first was Audemars Piguet, which is=
 a =E2=80=9Cvery progressive brand by nature,=E2=80=9D Wallner told me. The=
y have prioritized putting women in executive roles, starting with <strong>=
Ginny Wright </strong>as C.E.O. of the Americas in 2021, then <strong>Ilari=
a Resta </strong>as C.E.O. a couple years later.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
