><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">Mos=
t of the luxury watch brands you=E2=80=99ve heard of=E2=80=94Patek Philippe=
, Cartier, IWC, Jaeger-LeCoultre,
Audemars Piguet, etcetera=E2=80=94were founded in the 19th century, when th=
e industry almost exclusively made pocket watches for men. Women didn=E2=80=
=99t even have pockets back then. At the time, the mechanical movements tha=
t kept accurate time were too large to fit into anything smaller than a poc=
ket watch. Rolex invented the wristwatch as we know it in 1910; it became s=
tandard issue for enlisted men during World War I. Women didn=E2=80=99t rea=
lly start wearing wristwatches until the 1930s, after Jaeger-LeCoultre
created the Calibre 101, the world=E2=80=99s smallest mechanical movement a=
t just 14mm long by 4.8mm wide by 3.4mm thick.<br/><br/>Watches for women a=
re still dictated by size. A =E2=80=9Clady=E2=80=99s watch=E2=80=9D is defi=
ned as any watch smaller than 34 millimeters=E2=80=94usually built around a=
 battery-powered quartz movement instead of the mechanical complications th=
at make men=E2=80=99s watches rare and collectible, and featuring stereotyp=
ically =E2=80=9Cfeminine=E2=80=9D design details like mother-of-pearl. Thes=
e collections of =E2=80=9Cladies=E2=80=99 watches=E2=80=9D are
omnipresent but outdated, not only in design but also messaging. It=E2=80=
=99s no wonder that when Wallner started researching watches in 2019, she f=
ound =E2=80=9Cnothing for someone like me, young and into fashion.=E2=80=9D=
 Now, with her influence, Wallner is pushing for more intentionality in the=
 design rooms. Bulgari is committed to making mechanical watches for women,=
 and has released additional styles containing its proprietary Piccolissimo=
 movement. Tiffany is releasing more=E2=80=94and more fantastical=E2=80=94c=
reations, like
its =E2=80=9CBird on a Flying Tourbillon=E2=80=9D watch, which is in line w=
ith parent company LVMH=E2=80=99s growing focus on horology.<br/><br/>Femal=
e consumers are taking notice. They=E2=80=99re not yet collectors in the sa=
me way some male watch enthusiasts are=E2=80=94they=E2=80=99re more one or =
two and done, said Wallner=E2=80=94but with prices skyrocketing for other l=
uxury items like handbags, they=E2=80=99re looking to watches, which have m=
ore longevity. Wallner pointed out that vintage ladies=E2=80=99 watches are=
 also getting more popular. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sure in April at
the Watches and Wonders trade show in Geneva, there will be some <em>femme<=
/em>-forward releases=E2=80=94smaller sizes, more gems maybe,=E2=80=9D she =
said, =E2=80=9CThe watch world is really trying.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
